// Q1: Hofstede's Six Cultural Dimensions (MC - Remembering)
::W9-Q1-Hofstede-Six-Dimensions::What are the six cultural dimensions in Hofstede's framework?{
=Hofstede's six dimensions are\: Power Distance (PDI), Individualism vs. Collectivism (IDV), Masculinity vs. Femininity (MAS), Uncertainty Avoidance (UAI), Long-Term Orientation (LTO), and Indulgence vs. Restraint (IVR). These dimensions emerged from research with 117,000+ IBM employees across 76 countries and help explain systematic differences in how cultures approach hierarchy, identity, values, ambiguity, time, and gratification.#Power Distance, Individualism, Masculinity, Uncertainty Avoidance, Long-Term Orientation, Indulgence
~While these capture the opposite ends of some dimensions, Hofstede uses specific terminology. The dimensions are named for one end of the scale (e.g., "Individualism" not "Collectivism" as the dimension name), and the actual terms are Power Distance, Masculinity (not Femininity), Uncertainty Avoidance (not Risk Avoidance), Long-Term Orientation (not Short-Term), and Indulgence (not Restraint).#Power Distance, Collectivism, Femininity, Risk Avoidance, Short-Term Orientation, Restraint
~These are conceptual paraphrases but not the official dimension names from Hofstede's framework. Using standardized terminology is important for comparing cultures across the research literature and using tools like hofstede-insights.com.#Hierarchy, Independence, Achievement, Certainty, Future Focus, Freedom
~These terms capture some underlying concepts but aren't Hofstede's dimension names. Authority relates to Power Distance, and Identity relates to Individualism, but the framework uses specific labels that are standard across cross-cultural business research.#Authority, Identity, Values, Structure, Adaptation, Gratification
}

// Q2: Psychological Safety Definition (MC - Remembering)
::W9-Q2-Psychological-Safety-Definition::According to Amy Edmondson (1999), what is psychological safety?{
~This describes trust, not psychological safety. Edmondson explicitly distinguishes psychological safety from trust—trust is about expectations regarding others' future actions ("I believe you'll keep your word"), while safety is about the team climate being open to candor. You can have high trust but low psychological safety if the team punishes speaking up.#A team climate where members trust each other to keep commitments
=Edmondson defines psychological safety as "a shared belief held by members of a team that the team is safe for interpersonal risk taking." This means people feel comfortable asking questions, admitting mistakes, challenging the status quo, and offering wild ideas without fear of punishment, humiliation, or negative consequences to their status or career. It's about the overall team climate, not individual relationships.#A shared belief that the team is safe for interpersonal risk-taking
~Psychological safety is not the same as "being nice" or avoiding critical feedback. In fact, high psychological safety enables the candid, direct feedback that niceness often avoids. Safety means you can give and receive honest feedback without fear—it's about creating conditions for productive disagreement, not eliminating disagreement.#A leadership style that avoids giving negative feedback
~Group cohesiveness (everyone being nice, getting along) can actually reduce psychological safety because cohesive teams sometimes avoid challenging each other to preserve harmony (groupthink). Psychological safety requires comfort with disagreement and debate—it's about enabling voice, not enforcing niceness.#A team norm where everyone is nice and avoids disagreement
}

// Q3: Vietnam's Power Distance Score (MC - Remembering)
::W9-Q3-Vietnam-Power-Distance-Score::What is Vietnam's score on Hofstede's Power Distance dimension, and what does this indicate?{
~A score of 20 represents LOW power distance (like Denmark at 18), where hierarchy is minimal and all team members feel comfortable challenging authority. Vietnam's actual score is 70, indicating HIGH power distance where hierarchy is respected and expected.#20 (Low) – Hierarchy exists for convenience; flat organizational structures
~Vietnam doesn't fall in the moderate range on this dimension. With a score of 70, Vietnam has HIGH power distance, meaning hierarchical relationships are deeply embedded—managers lead decisively, subordinates show respect, and indirect disagreement preserves harmony.#40 (Moderate) – Balance between hierarchy and equality
=Vietnam scores 70 on Power Distance, which is HIGH. This means Vietnamese culture accepts and expects hierarchical relationships where power is distributed unequally. In practice\: managers expect to be obeyed, junior staff wait for senior approval before acting, speaking order respects seniority, and challenging authority directly would be seen as disrespectful. This affects communication through indirect disagreement and emphasis on face-saving.#70 (High) – Hierarchical society; managers expect obedience
~While 91 would represent extremely high power distance (like some Middle Eastern countries), Vietnam's score is 70—high but not extreme. The score of 70 does indicate strong respect for hierarchy, but Vietnamese culture also has moderate uncertainty avoidance (30), meaning some flexibility exists within hierarchical structures.#91 (Very High) – Extreme hierarchy; junior members never question seniors
}

// Q4: Meyer's Three A's of Feedback (Matching - Remembering)
::W9-Q4-Three-As-Matching::Match each of Meyer's Three A's to its definition\:
1. Aim to Assist
2. Actionable
3. Ask First

A) Feedback must include clear actions the recipient can take
B) Give feedback only with genuine intention to help, never to vent or assert dominance
C) Request feedback on your own work before giving feedback to others
{
=1-B, 2-A, 3-C#Perfect! Meyer's Three A's provide a framework for effective cross-cultural feedback\: (1) Aim to Assist means checking your motivation—feedback should help the recipient, not serve your ego; (2) Actionable means including specific steps they can take (vague criticism helps no one); (3) Ask First means requesting feedback reciprocally before giving it, which balances power dynamics and creates a feedback culture. Following all three prevents 90% of cross-cultural feedback disasters.
~Review the Three A's from the lecture. The Golden Rule Revised\: "Do unto others as THEY would have done unto themselves"—not as you would want it. All three principles work together\: good intent (Aim to Assist) + specific guidance (Actionable) + respectful process (Ask First) \= effective feedback across cultures. Remember Cassandra's case\: Miles violated "Ask First" by sending unrequested presentation tips.#Any other combination
}

// Q5: The Four Zones Framework (MC - Remembering)
::W9-Q5-Four-Zones-Learning-Zone::In Edmondson's Four Zones framework, which zone represents HIGH psychological safety and HIGH accountability?{
~The Comfort Zone has HIGH psychological safety but LOW accountability—teams are safe and comfortable, but there's no pressure to perform. This results in complacency with no growth. Common in student projects where everyone is friends but nobody pushes for excellence.#Comfort Zone
=The Learning Zone combines HIGH psychological safety + HIGH accountability, which is the optimal state for team performance. People can challenge each other's ideas (safety enables candor) AND everyone delivers on commitments (accountability drives execution). This is your goal for group presentations—create conditions where team members feel safe speaking up while also holding each other to high standards.#Learning Zone
~The Anxiety Zone has LOW psychological safety but HIGH accountability—there are high standards but people fear speaking up. This leads to fear-driven work, burnout, and organizational politics. Common in high-pressure corporate cultures where mistakes are punished. Vietnamese teams sometimes start here due to high power distance creating fear of challenging seniors.#Anxiety Zone
~The Apathy Zone has LOW psychological safety and LOW accountability—nobody cares about quality or climate. This is the worst outcome, characterized by minimal effort and "why bother?" attitudes. Teams reach this state when there are neither standards nor safety to improve them.#Apathy Zone
}

